@Tutorial(time: 25, title: "From Import to Export") {
    @Intro {
        This tutorial walks through the complete workflow: import SPC files, validate and analyze spectra, run AI analysis, use ML predictions, collaborate through enterprise tools, share results, and export reports.
    }

    @Section(title: "Import and Load") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            @Content {
                1. Open the Import tab in ``ContentView``.
                2. Use the file picker to select one or more `.spc` files.
                3. Review the parsed metadata and any warnings.
                4. Confirm the loaded spectra list in the sidebar.
                5. Optionally assign an instrument from the Instrument Registry for provenance tracking.

                Imported files are parsed by the SPC parser and stored with metadata in ``StoredDataset`` for faster reloading. Auxiliary metadata (application quantity, formulation type, post-irradiation state) is auto-extracted from filenames when possible.
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Analyze and Combine") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            @Content {
                1. Switch to the Analyze tab.
                2. Choose a processing pipeline: alignment, smoothing, baseline correction, and normalization.
                3. Toggle overlays and averages to compare multiple spectra.
                4. Inspect metrics like critical wavelength and UVA/UVB ratio from ``SpectralMetrics``.
                5. View CoreML SPF predictions with confidence intervals in the Inspector panel (when a trained model is available).

                Use ``ProcessingSettings`` to keep analysis repeatable across sessions. Compare ML predictions against analytical SPF estimates as a cross-validation check.
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "AI Analysis") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            @Content {
                1. Open Settings and configure one or more AI providers in the AI tab.
                2. Choose a prompt preset (``AIPromptPreset``) and scope (``AISelectionScope``).
                3. Run AI Analysis to generate summaries, comparisons, or formulation advice.
                4. Optionally enable Ensemble Mode to compare results from multiple providers side by side.

                AI analysis supports five providers: OpenAI, Claude, Grok, Gemini, and On-Device (Apple Intelligence). On-Device works fully offline with no API key. Configure provider priority, function-specific routing, and budget caps in Settings.
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "ML-Enhanced Prediction") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            @Content {
                1. Mark reference datasets with known in-vivo SPF values in Data Management.
                2. Open Settings and click Train Model in the ML Model section (macOS only).
                3. After training completes, review the R-squared and RMSE metrics.
                4. Return to the Analysis tab. CoreML predictions now appear in the Inspector panel.

                The model uses 122 features (111 spectral, 7 derived metrics, 4 auxiliary) and provides conformal prediction intervals for uncertainty quantification. See the ML Model Training guide for details.
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Enterprise Integration") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            @Content {
                1. Open Settings and go to the Enterprise tab.
                2. Enter your Microsoft 365 Client ID and Tenant ID, then sign in.
                3. Enable enterprise grounding to enrich AI analysis with organizational knowledge.
                4. Use the Enterprise tab to search M365 content, browse SharePoint files, or interact with Teams.

                Enterprise grounding injects context from SharePoint, OneDrive, and Copilot Connectors into AI analysis prompts. Citations show which documents informed the results.
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Share Results") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            @Content {
                1. Select datasets or generate a report.
                2. Use the Share menu to create a data package, chart snapshot, or export file.
                3. Choose a destination: Messages, AirDrop, Teams, email, or save to files.

                Data packages (`.spfpackage`) bundle datasets, settings, and AI results into a portable file. Recipients can open packages directly in PhysicAI. Chart snapshots export the current chart as a high-resolution PNG.
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Export and Report") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            @Content {
                1. Open the Reporting tab.
                2. Choose an ``ExportFormat`` (CSV, JCAMP, Excel, Word, PDF, or HTML).
                3. Add operator details and notes.
                4. Export locally, upload to SharePoint, or share to Teams.

                Exported outputs include spectrum data, processing settings, CoreML predictions, AI summaries, and metadata depending on your selections. PDF reports include vector-drawn charts, metrics tables, and tier badges.
            }
        }
    }
}
